14 "20-2-259.1.
15 (a) Subject to available funding, the State Board of Education shall provide matching
16 grants to qualified local units of administration to provide an eligible home reading
17 program for students in kindergarten through fourth grade. Such matching grant funds
18 shall be distributed by the Department of Education.
19 (b) A home reading program is eligible for matching grant funds provided pursuant to this
20 Code section if it is provided in partnership with an affiliated local unit of administration
21 by a nonprofit organization that meets the following requirements:
22 (1) Delivers an evidence based, self-selected reading program consisting of independent
23 reading level books that are individually mailed to the residences of or made available for
24 electronic download to students in kindergarten through fourth grade on a weekly basis;
25 (2) Incorporates at least weekly telephone calls, texts, or application notifications in
26 multiple languages to a parent or guardian to drive parental and family engagement
27 throughout the duration of the program;
28 (3) Builds on pedagogical principles of literacy instruction to scaffold fluency and
29 improve reading comprehension with student exercises;
30 (4) Includes a customizable portal to generate individualized data reports for analysis of
31 student progress by program providers, affiliated local units of administration, and
32 parents and guardians;
33 (5) Collects, disaggregates, and distributes detailed data on all metrics of the program,
34 such as engagement of parents or guardians, books read, and allowable demographic data;
35 (6) Provides a summary of data on all students served by the program to the Department
36 of Education;
37 (7) Agrees to secure the required matching funds from the participating local unit of
38 administration and maintain auditable verification of the receipt; and
39 (8) The combined total cost of the program, including district matching funds, does not
40 exceed $50.00 per student per semester.
